    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1970-06-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1970-06-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="319"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d319">
                <head>319. National Security Study Memorandum 95<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d319fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1"
                            >Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files, Box 365, Subject Files, <gloss target="#t_NSSM1"
                            >NSSM</gloss> 43–103. Top Secret; <gloss target="#t_NODIS1"
                            >Nodis</gloss>; Sensitive. A copy was sent to <persName
                            corresp="#p_WGEG1">Wheeler</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1970-06-06">June 6, 1970</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                    <item>The Director of Central Intelligence</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>U.S. Policy Objectives in Indo-China</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President has directed that a study be prepared on an urgent basis of U.S.
                    interests and the short-term U.S. policy alternatives in Indo-China, with
                    particular emphasis on the implications of the Cambodian situation.</p>
                <p>This study should be done on the assumption that there is no progress toward a
                    settlement in Indo-China through an international conference or other diplomatic
                    initiatives. It should include discussion of, but not be limited to, the
                    following subjects: <list>
                        <item>—Our interests and objectives in the current situation; e.g., the
                            degree to which we consider important the maintenance of a non-Communist
                            Cambodian Government.</item>
                        <item>—The steps which the U.S. might take directly or in support of other
                            countries to further those interests and objectives.</item>
                        <pb facs="1076" n="1040" xml:id="pg_1040"/>
                        <item>—The issues and options for U.S. policies if the Cambodian Government
                            falls.</item>
                        <item>—The effect of various U.S. actions on efforts toward reaching a
                            political settlement in Indo-China.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>The President has directed that this study be prepared by an ad hoc group chaired
                    by a representative of the Secretary of State and including representatives of
                    the addressees of the memorandum and of the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                    staff. It should be undertaken on a priority basis to enable it to be considered
                    concurrently with <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 94 and submitted by June
                    15, 1970.<note n="2" xml:id="d319fn2">The response to <gloss target="#t_NSSM1"
                            >NSSM</gloss> 95 was prepared on June 24. (Ibid.) It was not considered
                        concurrently with the response to <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 94;
                        see <ref target="#d336">Document 336</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Henry A. Kissinger</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
